Red Wine Quality Project

Leo Tay

08 February, 2016

Introduction:

Objective of the project is to determine which variables affect the quality of red wines and, if the variables affect each other. Dataset consists of 1599 red wines rated from 1 (Very Bad) to 10 (Very Excellent) quality. Each red wine has 11 chemical properties/variables.

Summary statistics for the variables in the dataset.

From the histogram, we can see that there are no ratings from 1 to 2 and 9 to 10, suggesting that while no wines were really bad, none were really good too (Subjective evaluation of quality). Based on the above, we can assume that the better/best quality range is 7 to 8.

Histograms of remaining variables

Create histograms of remaining variables to find out if there are any interesting results.

Histogram seems to be near normal distribution. Some outliers were noticed but as they are located near the remaining data, they will be included. Certain values have 0 counts suggesting that they had no effects or less likely, the red wines did not have those values.

Histogram contained far-right outlier, will try transformaing it.

I decided to avoid using Log10 transformations as based on calculations, there are negative values instead, I opted to retain 95% quantile of the data. From it, the histogram seems to be near bi-modal with some values having 0 counts. (I had also encountered some issues while transforming using Log10 which I will elborate further in the reflections section.)

Observed far-right outlier in histogram however, it does not seem to affect the distribution. Allowing outlier to remain. Multiple far-right outliers were observed and the histogram was difficult to read, will try to transform it.

Log transformation of historgram seems similar to the above and is in a normal distribution. Majority of the data seems to end around residual sugar 9.0. There are still outliers but they do not appear to affect the distribution.

As the two histograms does not seem to be discernable, I decided to retain 95% quantile of the data to filter the outliers. Histogram is similar to a normal distribution with some trailing data on the right. Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

Total of 1599 red wines are in the dataset with 13 variables (Fixed Acidity, Volatile Acidity, Citric Acid, Residual Sugar, Chlorides, Free Sulfur Dioxide, Total Sulfur Dioxide, Density, pH, Sulphates, Alcohol, X and, quality) X is used to identity each red wine while quality is used to indicate how good/bad the wine is.

No categorical variables were noticed in the dataset.

Other Observations:

  • Outliers were noticed in all variables
  • Median red wine quality is 6 and the highest is 8
  • Variable Density has the lowest peak count of 36 at value 0.99720

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

Main features are quality and Residual Sugar. Main goal is to determine what affects the quality of red wines. As Residual Sugar has the highest occurence among the wines, it seems logical that it in combination with other variables affect the quality.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

Based on my understanding, it seems that all the variables in the dataset affect the quality to some degree, be it taste, smell, health benefits or each other.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

No new variables were created as it will be hard to aggregate them into a total score of the variables.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

Majority of the variables were in near-normal distributions. Volatile Acidity seemed to be in a bi-modal distribution. Outliers were observed for all variables.

Quality vs Alcohol: There seems to be a relationship where increasing alcohol increases quality also however, effect seems to stop around where alcohol is 14. The increase in quality also seems to be limited as most red wines are located between quality 5 to 6. Quality 8 was first captured where alcohol is 9.8 and ended at 14.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

Alcohol has moderate correlation with quality while Sulphates, Citric Acid, Fixed Acidity and, Residual Sugar has low correlations.

Being the highest correlation observed, I was expecting the Quality vs Alcohol relationship where increasing alcohol increases quality to be more prominent. From the scatterplot, the increase was not as expected with alcohol values appearing on different quality values however, it was only between alcohol 9.8 to 14 that quality 8 started to appear more frequently.

For Sulpahtes, a similar pattern was observed where increasing between 0.63 to 1.10 results in quality of 8.

For Citric Acid, Fixed Acidity and Residual Sugar, quality 8 have been captured across their respective scales hence, increasing them should not result in higher quality values.

Throughout comparing Quality with Sulphates, Citric Acid, Fixed Acidity and, Residual Sugar, the majority of quality was found to be between 5 to 6.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?

Alcohol seems to have a relationship with Citric Acid however after creating the scatterplot, increasing citric acid does not seem to increase alcohol.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

Strongest relationship would still be Alcohol vs Quality. The plot has shown that while better quality wines have appeared with lower alcohol values, it is only when increasing alcohol that we see more wines with better quality.

Reflection

Dataset contained information about 1599 red wines across 12 variables.

I started by plotting histograms of all the variables to get a feel of how the data looked like. Initially, I thought that residual sugar would have the most impact on quality as it had the highest count of 156 at 2.0 meaning that it is present in around 10% of the red wines.

However after plotting out and subsetting the data, it was clear that this was not the case as the counts were mainly for quality 5 and 6.

Next, I plotted the correlation matrix and table. They showed that quality had relationships with alcohol (~0.48), sulphates (~0.26), citric acid (~0.23), fixed acidity (~0.12) and residual sugar (~0.01). After plotting scatterplots of quality against each of the variables above, it was observed that alcohol has the best relationship though limited and it was selected as the primary attribute.

Summary statistics of quality vs the other correlated variables were created and from there, the mean variable values were determined.

Lastly, I moved to creating scatterplots of quality vs alcohol and using the other variables to color-code the points. Based on the color, a range of the varibles creating quality 8 was noted.

  • Creating a prediction for quality was hard as it was evaluated/determined by humans where results may not be same if measured again
  • I was unable to include the remaining variables in the analysis in any meaning manner
  • Lack of a strong variable correlation with quality made the analysis much harder
  • Unable to create a new variable from existing ones (For example, using x, y and z from diamonds to form volume) as such relationships does not seem to exist in the dataset
